  "Epicenter": "",
  "Focus (hypocenter)": "",
  "Seismic zone": "",
  "The focus (or hypocenter) is the point within the Earth where rock first fractures and energy is released during an earthquake. The epicenter is the point on the surface directly above the focus.": "",
  "P-waves arrive first at seismic stations because they:": "",
  "Are the fastest seismic waves": "",
  "Are more destructive": "",
  "Travel only through rock": "",
  "Travel on the surface": "",
  "P-waves (primary waves) are compressional waves that travel faster than any other seismic wave type, reaching seismographs first. They can travel through solids, liquids, and gases, making them versatile in probing Earth's interior.": "",
  "Surface waves are the most destructive because they:": "",
  "Travel deep underground when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "Are the fastest waves under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Reach Earth's core, particularly regarding largest": "",
  "Move the ground in rolling and side-to-side motions at the surface": "",
  "Surface waves (Love and Rayleigh waves) travel along Earth's surface and produce the largest ground motions. Love waves cause horizontal shearing, while Rayleigh waves produce rolling motion, both of which are extremely damaging to structures.": "",
  "A magnitude 7 earthquake releases approximately _____ times more energy than a magnitude 6.": "",
  "About 32": "",
  "100 un": "",
  "2, par": "",
  "10, pa": "",
  "The moment magnitude scale is logarithmic: each whole number increase represents approximately 32 times more energy released. So a magnitude 7 earthquake releases about 32 times the energy of a magnitude 6.": "",
  "Earthquakes are located by measuring the time difference between:": "",
  "Magnitude and intensity": "",
  "Day and night seismic readings": "",
  "Surface waves only": "",
  "P-wave and S-wave arrivals at multiple stations": "",
  "Because P-waves and S-waves travel at different speeds, the time gap between their arrivals at a seismograph station indicates the distance to the earthquake. Data from at least three stations are used to triangulate the epicenter's location.": "",
  "The minimum number of seismograph stations needed to locate an epicenter is:": "",
  "2": "",
  "1": "",
  "10": "",
  "3": "",
  "Triangulation requires a minimum of three stations. Each station determines a distance circle from the epicenter based on the P-S wave time difference. The point where all three circles intersect is the epicenter.": "",
  "The Modified Mercalli Scale measures earthquake:": "",
  "Depth, particularly regarding": "",
  "Energy, particularly regarding": "",
  "Intensity based on observed effects and damage": "",
  "Magnitude, particularly regarding": "",
  "The Modified Mercalli Intensity scale (I-XII) measures the effects of an earthquake at a specific location, including how strongly shaking is felt, the damage to buildings, and ground effects. Unlike magnitude, intensity varies with distance from the epicenter.": "",
  "Most earthquakes occur along:": "",
  "Random locations across the globe": "",
  "Plate boundaries, especially convergent and transform boundaries": "",
  "Continental interiors": "",
  "Ocean surfaces": "",
  "About 90% of earthquakes occur along plate boundaries where tectonic stress is greatest. Convergent boundaries (subduction zones) and transform boundaries produce the most significant seismic activity.": "",
  "The moment magnitude scale replaced the Richter scale because it:": "",
  "Is simpler to use, particularly regarding distances under normal circumstances": "",
  "Works for all earthquake sizes and distances, while the Richter saturates at high magnitudes": "",
  "Only measures small earthquakes when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "Uses different instruments, particularly regarding magnitude according to": "",
  "The Richter scale becomes inaccurate for very large or very distant earthquakes because it saturates at high magnitudes. The moment magnitude scale measures the total seismic energy released and works reliably for earthquakes of all sizes and at all distances.": "",
  "The elastic rebound theory explains earthquakes as:": "",
  "Gradual, slow sliding along faults": "",
  "Sudden release of stored elastic energy when rock along a fault snaps back after stress exceeds its strength": "",
  "Vibrations caused by volcanic eruptions": "",
  "Movement caused by tidal forces from the Moon": "",
  "The elastic rebound theory states that rocks on either side of a fault deform elastically under tectonic stress until the stress exceeds the friction holding the fault locked. The rocks then suddenly snap back to their original shape, releasing energy as seismic waves.": "",
  "What is the epicenter of an earthquake?": "",
  "The point underground where the earthquake rupture begins": "",
  "The point on Earth's surface directly above the focus, where shaking is usually strongest": "",
  "The deepest point reached by seismic waves": "",
  "The farthest point from the earthquake where shaking can be felt": "",
  "The epicenter is the point on Earth's surface located directly above the focus (hypocenter) where the earthquake originated underground. Damage and shaking intensity are typically greatest near the epicenter.": "",
  "What is liquefaction?": "",
  "A phenomenon where saturated, loose soil loses its strength during earthquake shaking and behaves like a liquid": "",
  "The dissolving of rock by chemical weathering": "",
  "The melting of ice beneath glaciers during an earthquake": "",
  "The evaporation of groundwater caused by seismic heat": "",
  "Liquefaction occurs when water-saturated, loosely packed sediment loses its strength during seismic shaking and temporarily behaves like a liquid. This can cause buildings to sink, tilt, or collapse, and is a major hazard in areas built on unconsolidated fill or alluvial deposits.": "",
  "What is a seismograph?": "",
  "A device used to predict when earthquakes will occur": "",
  "A tool that measures the depth of Earth's crust": "",
  "An instrument that detects and records ground motion caused by seismic waves": "",
  "A map showing areas of earthquake risk": "",
  "A seismograph is an instrument that records ground vibrations produced by seismic waves. It works on the principle of inertia, with a suspended mass remaining relatively stationary while the ground and frame move beneath it, producing a seismogram.": "",
  "What is a tsunami?": "",
  "A tidal surge caused by the gravitational pull of the Moon": "",
  "A large ocean wave caused by strong winds during a hurricane": "",
  "A series of ocean waves generated by a sudden displacement of the ocean floor, typically from an underwater earthquake": "",
  "A whirlpool formed by converging ocean currents": "",
  "A tsunami is a series of powerful ocean waves caused by a sudden displacement of a large volume of water, most commonly triggered by an underwater earthquake. Tsunamis can cross entire ocean basins and reach heights of over 30 meters when they strike shore.": "",
  "What is a fault in geology?": "",
  "A fracture in Earth's crust along which blocks of rock have moved relative to each other": "",
  "A fold in rock layers caused by compression": "",
  "A zone where magma rises to the surface": "",
  "A crack in rock with no movement on either side": "",
  "A fault is a fracture or zone of fractures in Earth's crust along which there has been displacement of the sides relative to each other. Faults are classified by their motion: normal (tension), reverse (compression), and strike-slip (shear).": "",
  "What does 'seismology' mean?": "",
  "The study of ocean wave patterns and tides": "",
  "The scientific study of earthquakes and the propagation of seismic waves through the Earth": "",
  "The study of rock types and their classification": "",
  "The study of volcanic eruptions and their effects": "",
  "Seismology is the branch of geophysics that studies earthquakes and seismic waves. Seismologists analyze how waves travel through Earth's interior to understand both earthquake hazards and the structure of Earth's layers.": "",
  "What is an aftershock?": "",
  "The sound heard during an earthquake": "",
  "A small earthquake that occurs before the main earthquake": "",
  "A smaller earthquake that occurs after the main shock in the same area as the crust adjusts to the new stress distribution": "",
  "A seismic wave that bounces off Earth's core": "",
  "Aftershocks are smaller earthquakes that follow the main shock as the crust adjusts to the stress changes caused by the main rupture. They can continue for weeks, months, or even years and can cause additional damage to already-weakened structures.": "",
  "What is a P-wave?": "",
  "A wave that only travels through liquid layers of the Earth": "",
  "A wave generated only by volcanic eruptions": "",
  "A surface wave that causes the most destruction": "",
  "A primary compressional wave that is the fastest seismic wave and can travel through solids, liquids, and gases": "",
  "P-waves (primary waves) are compressional waves where particles move back and forth in the direction of wave travel, like a Slinky being pushed and pulled. They are the fastest seismic waves and can propagate through all states of matter.": "",
  "What is an S-wave?": "",
  "A wave that only travels through the inner core": "",
  "The slowest wave that causes the most damage": "",
  "A secondary shear wave that moves the ground perpendicular to its direction of travel and cannot pass through liquids": "",
  "A surface wave that travels along the ocean floor": "",
  "S-waves (secondary or shear waves) cause the ground to move side-to-side, perpendicular to the direction the wave travels. They are slower than P-waves and critically cannot travel through liquids, which revealed that Earth's outer core is liquid.": "",
  "What is a seismic hazard map?": "",
  "A map showing the locations of all active faults": "",
  "A map of all earthquakes that have occurred in recorded history": "",
  "A map showing areas with the highest probability of strong ground shaking, used to guide building codes and emergency planning": "",
  "A map that predicts exactly when and where earthquakes will occur": "",
  "Seismic hazard maps show the probability and expected intensity of ground shaking for different areas, based on historical seismicity, fault locations, and soil conditions. They are essential tools for building codes, land-use planning, and emergency preparedness.": "",
  "After a major earthquake, a city built on soft, water-saturated sediment experiences far more damage than a nearby city built on solid bedrock, even though both are the same distance from the epicenter. What phenomenon explains this difference?": "",
  "The city on bedrock had better building codes": "",
  "Soft sediment amplifies seismic waves and may undergo liquefaction, greatly increasing shaking intensity and damage compared to solid bedrock": "",
  "The earthquake was stronger on one side than the other": "",
  "Buildings on sediment are always older and weaker": "",
  "Soft, unconsolidated sediment amplifies seismic waves, causing stronger and longer shaking compared to solid bedrock. Additionally, saturated sediments may liquefy during shaking, causing the ground to behave like a fluid and buildings to sink or tilt.": "",
  "A seismologist at Station A records P-waves arriving 4 minutes before S-waves, while Station B records a P-S time difference of 8 minutes. What can be determined from this data?": "",
  "Station B is farther from the earthquake's epicenter than Station A because a larger P-S time gap indicates greater distance": "",
  "Station B experienced a stronger earthquake than Station A": "",
  "Station A's instruments are more sensitive than Station B's": "",
  "The earthquake occurred exactly between the two stations": "",
  "P-waves travel faster than S-waves, so the time gap between their arrivals increases with distance from the earthquake. A larger P-S time difference at Station B means it is farther from the epicenter, while Station A is closer.": "",
  "Japan invested heavily in earthquake-resistant building technology after past disasters. During the 2011 Tohoku earthquake (M9.1), most modern buildings survived the shaking. However, the majority of the approximately 20,000 deaths were caused by the subsequent tsunami. What lesson does this case study teach about earthquake preparedness?": "",
  "Earthquakes and tsunamis are completely unrelated events": "",
  "Building codes are unnecessary since the tsunami caused the most deaths": "",
  "Japan should have focused only on tsunami defenses and not earthquake-resistant buildings": "",
  "Comprehensive preparedness must address both direct earthquake effects and secondary hazards like tsunamis, liquefaction, and fires": "",
  "The Tohoku disaster shows that earthquake preparedness must be comprehensive. While earthquake-resistant buildings saved many lives during the shaking, the tsunami was a secondary hazard that proved far more deadly. Effective preparedness requires addressing multiple hazard types simultaneously.": "",
  "An insurance company is evaluating earthquake risk for a city located near two active faults. Fault A last ruptured 20 years ago, while Fault B has not ruptured in over 200 years. A geologist warns that Fault B may actually pose a greater near-term risk. Why?": "",
  "Older faults are always more dangerous than newer ones": "",
  "A long period without rupture on Fault B means more elastic strain has accumulated, potentially leading to a larger earthquake when it finally releases": "",
  "Fault A has already released all its energy and will never rupture again": "",
  "Fault B is dormant and will never produce an earthquake": "",
  "According to elastic rebound theory, tectonic stress accumulates along a locked fault over time. A fault that has not ruptured in 200 years may have accumulated enormous strain, making it capable of producing a very large earthquake. This concept is known as a seismic gap.": "",
  "During an earthquake drill at a school, students are instructed to 'Drop, Cover, and Hold On' rather than running outside. Why is this the recommended action during an earthquake?": "",
  "Earthquakes only cause damage to the outside of buildings": "",
  "Running outside is impossible during an earthquake because doors lock automatically": "",
  "Schools are built to collapse inward, making the inside safer than the outside": "",
  "Most earthquake injuries occur from falling debris; taking cover under a sturdy desk protects against falling objects, while running increases the risk of being struck": "",
  "Most earthquake injuries are caused by falling objects, shattering glass, and collapsing materials. Taking cover under a sturdy desk or table protects from these hazards, while attempting to run increases the risk of being struck by debris or falling.": "",
  "After a M6.2 earthquake in central Italy in 2016, many historic stone buildings collapsed while modern reinforced concrete structures survived. What engineering principle explains this difference?": "",
  "Modern buildings are lighter and therefore unaffected by earthquakes": "",
  "Modern earthquake-resistant buildings are designed to flex and absorb seismic energy, while rigid unreinforced stone structures are brittle and collapse under lateral forces": "",
  "Historic buildings were damaged by earlier earthquakes, not the current one": "",
  "Stone buildings attract more seismic energy than concrete buildings": "",
  "Earthquake-resistant design incorporates flexibility and energy absorption (through steel reinforcement, base isolation, and dampers) that allow buildings to sway without collapsing. Unreinforced masonry is rigid and brittle, crumbling when subjected to the lateral forces of an earthquake.": "",
  "A news report states that a magnitude 5.0 earthquake was felt over a wide area but caused minimal damage, while a magnitude 4.5 earthquake in a different region collapsed several buildings and caused deaths. How is this possible if the first earthquake had a higher magnitude?": "",
  "The magnitude scale is inaccurate and should not be trusted": "",
  "The M4.5 earthquake was actually stronger but was measured incorrectly": "",
  "Earthquake damage depends on many factors beyond magnitude, including depth, soil type, building quality, and population density": "",
  "Smaller earthquakes always cause more damage than larger ones": "",
  "Magnitude measures energy released, but damage depends on many factors: depth (shallow earthquakes cause more damage), soil conditions (soft sediment amplifies shaking), building construction quality, and population density. A smaller earthquake in a vulnerable area can be far more destructive.": "",
  "Scientists cannot currently predict exactly when and where the next major earthquake will occur. Despite this limitation, a city can still significantly reduce earthquake casualties. Which combination of strategies would be most effective?": "",
  "Enforcing strict building codes, creating early warning systems, conducting public education drills, and using seismic hazard maps for land-use planning": "",
  "Installing earthquake prediction machines on every street corner": "",
  "Evacuating the entire city permanently to avoid all earthquake risk": "",
  "Building all structures underground where earthquakes cannot reach": "",
  "While earthquake prediction remains unreliable, a combination of preparedness measures can dramatically reduce casualties. Japan's 2011 experience shows that strict building codes, early warning systems, community drills, and smart land-use planning save far more lives than any prediction technology could.": "",
  "A homeowner in a seismically active region is deciding between building on a lot with solid granite bedrock and a lot with deep, sandy soil near a river. A geologist advises choosing the bedrock site. What is the scientific basis for this recommendation?": "",
  "Granite looks better as a foundation material, particularly regarding increasing when evaluated systematically": "",
